00081 /* why this horrible mess? It's always been a tradeoff-- tons of structs,
00082    each storing it's specific lists of goodies, or a 'simple' single struct,
00083    with lots of fields, that catches all uses at once. Either you have a long
00084    list of struct names and subnames, or you have a long list of field names,
00085    and where/how they are used. I'm going with a single struct, using unions
00086    to reduce storage. Some simple generalizations, and a long list of types,
00087    and a book about what is used with what types.... Sorry!
00088 */
00089 
00090 struct pval
00091 {
00092    pvaltype type;
00093    int startline;
00094    int endline;
00095    int startcol;
00096    int endcol;
00097    char *filename;
00098    
00099    union
00100    {
00101       char *str; /* wow, used almost everywhere! */
00102       struct pval *list; /* used in SWITCHES, ESWITCHES, INCLUDES, STATEMENTBLOCK, GOTO */
00103       struct pval *statements;/*  used in EXTENSION */
00104       char *for_init;  /* used in FOR */
00105    } u1;
00106    struct pval *u1_last; /* to build in-order lists -- looks like we only need one */
00107    
00108    union
00109    {
00110       struct pval *arglist; /* used in macro_call, application_call, MACRO def, also attached to PWORD, the 4 timevals for includes  */
00111       struct pval *statements; /* used in case, default, catch, while's statement, CONTEXT elements, GLOBALS */
00112       char *val;  /* used in VARDEC */
00113       char *for_test; /* used in FOR */
00114       int label_in_case; /* a boolean for LABELs */
00115       struct pval *goto_target;  /* used in GOTO */
00116    } u2;
00117    
00118    union
00119    {
00120       char *for_inc; /* used in FOR */
00121       struct pval *else_statements; /* used in IF */
00122       struct pval *macro_statements; /* used in MACRO */
00123       int abstract;  /* used for context */
00124       char *hints; /* used in EXTENSION */
00125       int goto_target_in_case; /* used in GOTO */
00126       struct ael_extension *compiled_label;
00127    } u3;
00128    
00129    union
00130    {
00131       struct pval *for_statements; /* used in PV_FOR */
00132       int regexten;                /* used in EXTENSION */
00133    } u4;
00134    
00135    struct pval *next; /* the pval at the end of this ptr will ALWAYS be of the same type as this one! 
00136                     EXCEPT for objects of the different types, that are in the same list, like contexts & macros, etc */
00137    
00138    struct pval *dad; /* the 'container' of this struct instance */
00139    struct pval *prev; /* the opposite of the 'next' pointer */
00140 } ;
